Creatrix Execution Contract

1. Core Principle

Creatrix must behave identically in all environments.

No behaviour may depend on:

hosting platform (Replit, local, cloud, etc.)
runtime injection systems
external “magic” SDKs
invisible infrastructure assumptions

If behaviour changes by environment → it is a bug, not a feature.

🔌 2. Tool Architecture Rule
2.1 No implicit tool activation

A tool is only active if:

explicitly configured in .env or settings
explicitly instantiated in code
explicitly validated at runtime

If any of those are missing:

the tool is OFF. No fallback, no proxy, no inference.

2.2 No dual-path execution

Forbidden pattern:

if (replit) use SDK
else use direct API

Allowed pattern:

use direct API with explicit credentials

Replit-specific behaviour is treated as external tooling noise, not logic.

🔐 3. Identity & Configuration Rule
3.1 All credentials are user-owned
.env is canonical
no platform overwrites allowed
no secret injection from runtime environments
3.2 No hidden mutation of config

Creatrix must never:

rewrite .env
auto-inject keys
silently patch config based on environment

If config is missing:

fail explicitly

🧱 4. Platform Independence Rule

Creatrix must NOT assume:

Replit runtime exists
connectors SDK exists
cloud auth proxy exists
hosted filesystem identity exists

If those exist → they are ignored unless explicitly configured.

⚠️ 5. Failure Behaviour Rule

When something is misconfigured:

MUST:
fail loudly
log explicit missing dependency
stop tool activation
MUST NOT:
degrade silently
fall back to alternate runtime behaviour
guess intent
“helpfully adapt”
🧠 6. State Ownership Rule

All persistent state belongs to:

the local filesystem / repo / explicit database

NOT:

platform cache
Replit-managed state
hidden connector state
runtime memory injection
🔄 7. Tool Registry Rule

Tool availability is determined ONLY by:

explicit registration in Creatrix config
successful runtime validation check

NOT by:

UI presence
partial imports
SDK availability
environment detection

🧭 8. Replit-Specific Rule (important for my next project)

If running in Replit:

treat Replit connectors as OPTIONAL external adapters
NEVER allow them to define core behaviour
NEVER rely on them for correctness

Replit is a host, not a logic layer.

🧬 9. Mental Model Rule (this is the stabiliser)

Creatrix must always assume:

“I know nothing unless explicitly told in config or code.”

No inference layers.
No environment assumptions.
No hidden intelligence from platform.

☕ What this gives you (why this matters)

This contract guarantees:

Notion behaves the same everywhere
tools don’t randomly disappear
Replit cannot “shape” behaviour silently
local system remains authoritative
your writing graph stays stable and portable
